You do not need to tensor with $R$. You can use other rings like $Q$, $C$ or $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$. You can verify that for $C$ it holds that:

$(\mathbb{Z}^{a_0} \oplus (\prod_{i\in\mathbb{N}} (\mathbb{Z}/i\mathbb{Z})^{a_i})) \otimes_{\mathbb{Z}} C \simeq C^{a_0}$;

the statement is analogous for $Q$. The case of $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$ is more interesting, as $\mathbb{Z}/q\mathbb{Z} \otimes_{\mathbb{Z}} \mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$ need not be trivial (e.g. if $p = q$ then we obtain simply $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$).

The following results hold:
\begin{itemize}
\item $\pi_1(\Sigma_g, p) \cong \langle a_1, b_1, \ldots, a_g, b_g | \prod_{i=1}^g[a_i, b_i]\rangle$.
\item $H_1(\Sigma_g, \mathbb{Z}) \cong \mathbb{Z}^{2g}$.
\item $H_1(\Sigma_g, \mathbb{R}) \cong \mathbb{R}^{2g}$.
\end{itemize}

A map $\pi : Y \to X$ satisfies the homotopy lifting property if any commutative diagram

\begin{array}{ccc}
A \times \{0\} & \stackrel{\iota}{\hookrightarrow} & A \times [0, 1] \\
\tilde{f}\downarrow & & \downarrow F \\
Y & \stackrel{\pi}{\to} & X
\end{array}

extends to

\begin{array}{ccc}
A \times \{0\} & \stackrel{\iota}{\hookrightarrow} & A \times [0, 1] \\
\tilde{f}\downarrow & & \downarrow \tilde{F} \\
Y & \stackrel{\pi}{\to} & X
\end{array}

That is: we are given a homotopy $F$ of $A$ into $X$ and a lift $\tilde{f}$ of its starting map $f = F(-, 0)$. Then, the property says that we are able to find a homotopy $\tilde{F}$ of $\tilde{f}$, lifting $F$.

A map $\pi : Y \to X$ satisfies the path lifting property if, given a path $\gamma : I = [0, 1] \to X$ and a lift $\tilde{\gamma}(0)$ of its initial point $\gamma(0)$, we can always find a lift $\tilde{\gamma}$ completing the diagram:

\begin{array}{ccc}
\{0\} & \stackrel{\iota}{\hookrightarrow} & I \\
\tilde{\gamma}(0)\downarrow & & \downarrow \gamma \\
Y & \stackrel{\pi}{\to} & X
\end{array}
